WEBVTT

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:43.500
KINGSLEY:
In Cairo, a muezzin calls
faithful Muslims to prayer.

00:00:49.130 --> 00:00:53.660
It's the same call that sounds
five times a day, every day

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:55.830
in cities across the world.

00:00:55.830 --> 00:01:02.000
(<i> muezzin continues calling</i> )

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.160
Nearly a quarter of the people
on Earth respond to it

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:09.900
bound together by the enduring
spirit of Islam.

00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:20.200
(<i> muezzin continues calling</i> )

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:26.560
"God is most great,"
the muezzin calls.

00:01:26.560 --> 00:01:32.700
"I testify there is
no other god but God."

00:01:32.700 --> 00:01:41.030
"I testify Muhammad is
the messenger of God."

00:01:41.030 --> 00:01:43.900
"Come and pray...

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:48.060
"come and flourish.

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:51.760
"God is most great.

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:55.700
There is no god but God."

00:01:55.700 --> 00:01:57.000
(<i> muezzin finishes prayer</i> )

00:02:04.530 --> 00:02:07.860
In the unfolding of history,
Islamic civilization

00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:11.300
has been one of humanity's
grandest achievements...

00:02:14.730 --> 00:02:20.100
a worldwide power founded
simply on faith;

00:02:20.100 --> 00:02:21.800
a spiritual revolution

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:25.500
that would shape the nations
of three continents

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:27.160
and launch an empire.

00:02:31.430 --> 00:02:34.560
For the West, much
of the history of Islam

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:39.160
has been obscured behind a veil
of fear and misunderstanding.

00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:41.160
Yet Islam's hidden history

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:43.930
is deeply and
surprisingly interwoven

00:02:43.930 --> 00:02:48.360
with Western civilization.

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:49.660
It was Muslim scholars

00:02:49.660 --> 00:02:52.360
who reclaimed the ancient wisdom
of the Greeks

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:57.430
while Europe languished
in the Dark Ages.

00:02:57.430 --> 00:03:00.800
It was they who sowed the seeds
of the Renaissance

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:04.000
600 years before the birth
of Leonardo da Vinci.

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:12.130
From the way we heal the sick

00:03:12.130 --> 00:03:16.100
to the numerals
we use for counting

00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:19.060
cultures across the globe

00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:25.100
have been shaped
by Islamic civilization.

00:03:25.100 --> 00:03:30.860
But all this began with the life
of a single ordinary man.

00:03:30.860 --> 00:03:33.400
And the profound message
he proclaimed

00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:37.430
would change the world forever.

00:03:37.430 --> 00:03:40.960
His name was Muhammad.

00:04:04.200 --> 00:04:11.100
[Captioning sponsored
 by VIEWERS LIKE YOU]

00:04:19.330 --> 00:04:23.600
KINGSLEY:
To Muslims, the life of Muhammad
is a story revered.

00:04:23.600 --> 00:04:27.000
In its mysteries as much
as its certainties

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.430
there are beliefs held sacred.

00:04:29.430 --> 00:04:31.730
MAN:
Whatever we can tell about
the Prophet, of course

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:33.060
is screened through the filter

00:04:33.060 --> 00:04:35.060
of what has been preserved
over the centuries

00:04:35.060 --> 00:04:37.100
and what people
have wanted to preserve.

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:39.030
And it's very difficult
to pull out

00:04:39.030 --> 00:04:43.430
from all of these different
sources that are very adoring

00:04:43.430 --> 00:04:48.360
the ordinary human being that...
the... the person that he was.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:05:00.360
KINGSLEY:
We do know that Muhammad
was born in or around 570 AD

00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:03.630
in the sun-blasted
Arabian peninsula...

00:05:06.660 --> 00:05:10.160
a land of savage scarcity
whose Bedouin tribes

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:13.730
were locked in a constant state
of tribal war.

00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:21.100
While still an infant

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:24.560
Muhammad's parents gave him
his first taste

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:26.400
of life in the desert.

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:30.400
MAN:
Muhammad was from a town, Mecca

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:32.700
but he was sent off to live
with the Bedouin

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:35.000
because the people even
in the town of Mecca

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
felt that the Bedouin
were the holders

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:39.200
of the... the deeper
cultural Arab values.

00:05:42.060 --> 00:05:44.200
And the Bedouin view
the townspeople

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:47.760
as having lost their really
authentic roots in Arab culture

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:50.700
and the poetry and...
and animal husbandry

00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:54.130
and all the things that they...
they do so well.

00:05:54.130 --> 00:05:57.630
(<i> goat bleating</i> )

00:05:57.630 --> 00:06:02.830
KINGSLEY:
By the time Muhammad was six,
both of his parents had died

00:06:02.830 --> 00:06:05.800
and he was taken under
the protection of his uncle

00:06:05.800 --> 00:06:07.200
chief of his clan.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:12.560
Being an outsider gave him
a singular perspective.

00:06:12.560 --> 00:06:16.730
He'd been orphaned early
and developed very early on

00:06:16.730 --> 00:06:19.130
a passionate sense of concern

00:06:19.130 --> 00:06:22.200
for those who are
left out of society.

00:06:22.200 --> 00:06:25.030
To be orphaned
in a tribal society

00:06:25.030 --> 00:06:27.900
where clan and
family relationships

00:06:27.900 --> 00:06:29.900
are your keys to everything--

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:32.160
success, status,
honor, dignity--

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:36.600
is... is to face what it really
feels like to be marginalized.

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:40.400
And that obviously had a...
a very deep impression on him

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:41.430
as a young man.

00:06:44.100 --> 00:06:47.100
WOMAN:
In some ways it was
detrimental, of course

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:48.800
to grow up without parents

00:06:48.800 --> 00:06:51.400
but in other ways
he was so adaptable.

00:06:51.400 --> 00:06:52.860
He had many parents--

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:55.630
he had many fathers,
he had many mothers

00:06:55.630 --> 00:06:58.100
so it made him a child
of everybody.

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:01.400
(<i> bells tinkling</i> )

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:05.860
KINGSLEY:
Muhammad's clan, like Arabs
all across the Arabian peninsula

00:07:05.860 --> 00:07:07.400
would share the stories

00:07:07.400 --> 00:07:10.400
that had been told and retold
for generations.

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:13.460
(<i> man speaking Arabic</i> )

00:07:13.460 --> 00:07:17.730
MAN:
Pre-Islamic Arabian civilization
was largely an oral culture

00:07:17.730 --> 00:07:21.900
and there was tremendous respect
for and admiration for people

00:07:21.900 --> 00:07:24.230
who could express
themselves orally

00:07:24.230 --> 00:07:26.200
and especially those
who could recite poetry

00:07:26.200 --> 00:07:27.630
almost at the drop of a hat.

00:07:27.630 --> 00:07:30.960
Some of the most important
people in a tribe were the poets

00:07:30.960 --> 00:07:33.660
because they sang
of the glory of the tribe;

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:36.130
they... they told
the story of the tribe.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:43.130
KINGSLEY:
To the Bedouin, the word
had a mystical importance.

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:48.300
Poets linked the tribe
to its ancestors

00:07:48.300 --> 00:07:52.900
and celebrated values
older than memory.

00:07:52.900 --> 00:07:56.030
Poetry was the sinew
that bound the Bedouin together

00:07:56.030 --> 00:08:00.100
celebrating their victories,
lamenting their defeats.

00:08:00.100 --> 00:08:01.760
SELLS:
The poems themselves

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:06.900
like the poems of Homer
both celebrate this heroic ethos

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:10.200
and yet intimate,
in the deepest way

00:08:10.200 --> 00:08:12.730
the tragedy that this war--

00:08:12.730 --> 00:08:17.860
this ethos of constant tribal
warfare brings to people.

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:24.460
KINGSLEY:
Warfare and conflict
were the grim realities

00:08:24.460 --> 00:08:27.860
of a dangerous time.

00:08:27.860 --> 00:08:31.330
Muhammad's uncle taught him
the skills he'd need to survive

00:08:31.330 --> 00:08:34.900
in a world where even a prophet
would wield a bow and arrow.

00:08:42.500 --> 00:08:46.630
In a wilderness punished by
the elements and bereft of water

00:08:46.630 --> 00:08:48.500
rivalry over a single well

00:08:48.500 --> 00:08:50.960
could provoke a blood feud
for generations.

00:08:54.030 --> 00:08:56.100
ATIL:
A real rivalry, real battle

00:08:56.100 --> 00:08:58.530
would have been sometimes
quite bloody

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:02.660
so the allegiance of individuals
was to the family, immediately

00:09:02.660 --> 00:09:05.230
and, at a larger extent,
to the tribe.

00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:12.730
KINGSLEY:
Without the tribe's protection,
no one could endure.

00:09:12.730 --> 00:09:16.430
Scattered across the peninsula
were countless factions

00:09:16.430 --> 00:09:18.700
all embroiled
in bitter struggles

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:21.930
each defending its precious
grazing lands, trade routes

00:09:21.930 --> 00:09:24.730
and, most importantly,
its wells.

00:09:26.930 --> 00:09:28.600
BLOOM:
Well, you have to understand

00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:30.630
I mean, most
of the lands are dry

00:09:30.630 --> 00:09:33.200
and so water is...
is something that's...

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:35.400
everyone always
considers precious.

00:09:39.530 --> 00:09:44.000
SELLS:
For those of us in climates
that are more heavily watered

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.030
it's difficult to understand

00:09:46.030 --> 00:09:50.260
the depth and the centrality
of the symbol of water

00:09:50.260 --> 00:09:52.800
in societies that are desert

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:57.030
and in which it only rains
once or twice a year

00:09:57.030 --> 00:09:58.730
and in which a little water

00:09:58.730 --> 00:10:01.460
makes the difference
between life and death.

00:10:03.600 --> 00:10:07.060
(<i> drums beating,
 metal clanking</i> )

00:10:07.060 --> 00:10:11.330
KINGSLEY:
Each clan had its own separate
gods and totems...

00:10:11.330 --> 00:10:16.530
to water and wind,
fire and night.

00:10:16.530 --> 00:10:19.900
They were kept in
the caravan town of Mecca

00:10:19.900 --> 00:10:22.830
in a shrine of wood,
stone and cloth.

00:10:22.830 --> 00:10:27.200
It was called the<i> "Ka'bah,"</i>
the Arabic word for cube.

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:30.230
RENARD:
Pre-Islamic Arabs worshipped
a number of spirits

00:10:30.230 --> 00:10:32.900
and they were generally
nature-oriented spirits

00:10:32.900 --> 00:10:37.200
sometimes associated
with natural... natural features

00:10:37.200 --> 00:10:39.800
like trees or rocks or springs.

00:10:39.800 --> 00:10:44.660
And the<i> Ka'bah</i> in Mecca was one
of a number of these sanctuaries

00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:48.330
centered around a particular
cluster of deities.

00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:53.530
KINGSLEY:
It was said the Hebrew patriarch
Abraham, himself

00:10:53.530 --> 00:10:56.460
built the<i> Ka'bah</i>
centuries before

00:10:56.460 --> 00:11:00.630
and that a sacred black stone
it held within

00:11:00.630 --> 00:11:03.300
had fallen from the sky.

00:11:03.300 --> 00:11:05.660
In these turbulent times

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:09.760
the<i> Ka'bah</i> provided
a rare place of peace.

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:13.600
Only here would the Bedouins
submit to a temporary truce

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:17.330
before returning to their
conflicts of the open sands.

00:11:18.800 --> 00:11:22.900
There was this one place
in the middle, around the<i> Ka'bah</i>

00:11:22.900 --> 00:11:25.860
which was, from
even pre-Islamic times...

00:11:25.860 --> 00:11:28.860
was a place of...
a sacred enclosure

00:11:28.860 --> 00:11:31.900
where all people had
to put down their arms.

00:11:31.900 --> 00:11:34.700
And this, of course,
facilitated trading

00:11:34.700 --> 00:11:38.200
because it meant that you
couldn't carry on your feuds

00:11:38.200 --> 00:11:41.060
when you were doing
your buying and selling.

00:11:44.060 --> 00:11:46.260
The spiritual
and economic importance

00:11:46.260 --> 00:11:48.930
of the<i> Ka'bah</i> in Mecca
are pretty hard to separate

00:11:48.930 --> 00:11:51.730
in... as far as the pre-Islamic
Arabs are concerned.

00:11:54.330 --> 00:11:58.900
KINGSLEY:
The<i> Ka'bah</i> made Mecca
a vibrant center for trade.

00:11:58.900 --> 00:12:01.960
Here were found Arabian incense

00:12:01.960 --> 00:12:05.060
exotic perfumes
and Indian spices

00:12:05.060 --> 00:12:08.430
Chinese silks
and Egyptian linens.

00:12:11.530 --> 00:12:14.060
But perhaps the greatest
treasure to be found in Mecca

00:12:14.060 --> 00:12:15.630
was the rich mixture
of cultures.

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:22.230
MAN:
There were people
who came through town

00:12:22.230 --> 00:12:24.800
who had all kinds
of interesting experiences

00:12:24.800 --> 00:12:26.500
to relate of faraway places.

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:27.930
The local religion was mixed.

00:12:27.930 --> 00:12:29.060
There were Christians.

00:12:29.060 --> 00:12:30.330
There were Jews.

00:12:30.330 --> 00:12:32.530
And there were also
the Arabs of the desert

00:12:32.530 --> 00:12:34.260
who followed an animist
type of religion.

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:41.400
KINGSLEY:
Muhammad's world
was a center of trade

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:44.800
connecting the Mediterranean Sea
to the Indian Ocean

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:48.000
linking the aging empires
of Byzantium and Persia

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.860
to the great bazaars
of India and China.

00:13:02.630 --> 00:13:07.160
Muhammad became a merchant.

00:13:07.160 --> 00:13:12.200
In fact, he had
a great flair for trade.

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:16.700
At the age of 25, while leading
a caravan northward to Syria

00:13:16.700 --> 00:13:20.460
his talents caught the eye
of the shipment's owner

00:13:20.460 --> 00:13:24.700
a wealthy widow named Khadijah.

00:13:24.700 --> 00:13:29.960
She was so taken with Muhammad,
she proposed marriage.

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:31.460
ATIL:
Ah, Khadijah.

00:13:31.460 --> 00:13:35.300
Well, I think she was a mentor,
as well as a wife.

00:13:35.300 --> 00:13:38.660
A very strong lady,
who had her own business

00:13:38.660 --> 00:13:40.600
and Muhammad was
helping her out.

00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:42.530
So it was a wonderful
partnership

00:13:42.530 --> 00:13:44.830
and I'm sure he learned
a lot from her.

00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:49.130
He had a tremendous
amount of contact

00:13:49.130 --> 00:13:53.100
with merchants coming from
different parts of the world

00:13:53.100 --> 00:13:58.060
passing through
the Arabian Peninsula.

00:13:58.060 --> 00:13:59.460
I think he was

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:02.960
a very intelligent man,
very open-minded

00:14:02.960 --> 00:14:07.630
and he was able to communicate
with a great variety of peoples.

00:14:07.630 --> 00:14:11.700
He must have had
great charisma as well.

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:14.160
KINGSLEY:
Muhammad had a way with people

00:14:14.160 --> 00:14:16.730
and with resolving
their disputes.

00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:21.400
Once, when the Ka'bah
fell into disrepair

00:14:21.400 --> 00:14:26.160
the clan chieftains quarreled
over who would have the honor

00:14:26.160 --> 00:14:30.830
of putting the sacred black
stone back where it belonged.

00:14:30.830 --> 00:14:33.160
Before violence could erupt

00:14:33.160 --> 00:14:37.330
Muhammad proposed
an equitable solution.

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:45.560
United in the effort

00:14:45.560 --> 00:14:49.430
the four leaders shared
the weight and the honor.

00:14:52.460 --> 00:14:54.030
In gratitude

00:14:54.030 --> 00:14:59.600
they invited Muhammad himself
to replace the sacred stone.

00:14:59.600 --> 00:15:04.530
He became known as
"al-Ameen, the Trusted One."

00:15:04.530 --> 00:15:06.330
DENNY:
There are all kinds
of indications

00:15:06.330 --> 00:15:07.930
that he was
tremendously interested

00:15:07.930 --> 00:15:09.430
in religious questions.

00:15:09.430 --> 00:15:11.060
This is obviously not something

00:15:11.060 --> 00:15:13.930
that an ordinary person
probably was interested in

00:15:13.930 --> 00:15:15.230
in those days.

00:15:15.230 --> 00:15:21.160
He talked to sages...
Arab sages.

00:15:21.160 --> 00:15:24.660
He talked to Jewish
and Christian sages

00:15:24.660 --> 00:15:26.260
who lived in the area.

00:15:26.260 --> 00:15:29.130
He used to go up into
the rock hills around Mecca

00:15:29.130 --> 00:15:32.730
and meditate,
think about things.

00:15:32.730 --> 00:15:36.200
And at some point,
had this extraordinary vision

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:40.700
which is spoken about
very evocatively and elusively.

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:49.200
KINGSLEY:
In a cave above Mecca,
Muhammad had

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:56.830
an experience that would be
the defining moment of his life.

00:15:56.830 --> 00:16:01.730
An angel was said to appear
before him in the form of a man

00:16:01.730 --> 00:16:03.260
instructing him to recite

00:16:03.260 --> 00:16:07.500
in the name of God,
the Almighty.

00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:09.900
For Muhammad,
it was an encounter

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:13.600
as profound as it
was deeply disturbing.

00:16:13.600 --> 00:16:15.560
SELLS:
You get a sense

00:16:15.560 --> 00:16:19.830
of what it would be like to be
a normal person in society

00:16:19.830 --> 00:16:24.100
perhaps unusual in the sense
of your intensity for things

00:16:24.100 --> 00:16:29.000
like social justice, and finding
out what the meaning of life is

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.160
but not being endowed

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:36.000
with anything that would seem
miraculous by your friends

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.100
and all of a sudden

00:16:38.100 --> 00:16:42.260
having this voice come to you
and then come out of you

00:16:42.260 --> 00:16:45.330
as you speak it and
recite it to other people.

00:16:49.860 --> 00:16:52.700
And that is the beginning

00:16:52.700 --> 00:16:55.130
of the prophetic career
of Muhammad.

00:17:00.360 --> 00:17:05.660
KINGSLEY:
The months to come
would bring more revelations--

00:17:05.660 --> 00:17:09.100
powerful words
of a lyrical quality

00:17:09.100 --> 00:17:13.460
more beautiful than the most
exquisite Arabic poetry.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:21.500
Above all, Muhammad was to bear
one message to his people:

00:17:21.500 --> 00:17:24.630
a simple yet
radical proclamation

00:17:24.630 --> 00:17:28.900
that there is only one God.

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:30.600
DENNY:
The central tenet of Islam

00:17:30.600 --> 00:17:35.400
is the oneness,
the indivisible unity of God;

00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:39.530
not something that is simply...
that one pays lip service to

00:17:39.530 --> 00:17:43.730
but something that is absolutely
the most important concept.

00:17:43.730 --> 00:17:45.630
Divine unity is more than saying

00:17:45.630 --> 00:17:49.330
God is... there's only one God
and there are no other deities.

00:17:49.330 --> 00:17:52.360
It's only thinking
about one thing.

00:17:52.360 --> 00:17:54.560
So to be thinking
about possessions

00:17:54.560 --> 00:17:58.130
to be thinking about status,
to be thinking about power

00:17:58.130 --> 00:18:00.430
are all intellectual idols.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.060
KINGSLEY:
The implications
were staggering.

00:18:09.060 --> 00:18:12.700
One god meant one people.

00:18:12.700 --> 00:18:15.830
No more tribal divisions.

00:18:15.830 --> 00:18:20.730
To the poor and unprotected,
the prospect was revolutionary.

00:18:22.960 --> 00:18:25.260
RENARD:
It seems to me

00:18:25.260 --> 00:18:27.930
that one of the most important
things in his early teaching

00:18:27.930 --> 00:18:29.700
that isn't often talked about

00:18:29.700 --> 00:18:32.160
is the strong social justice
message that he delivered.

00:18:33.730 --> 00:18:36.900
In the Mecca of the time, there
was an increasing separation

00:18:36.900 --> 00:18:38.560
between the haves and have-nots.

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:40.060
He insisted that it...

00:18:40.060 --> 00:18:42.600
this was not to be, and
that we should share the wealth

00:18:42.600 --> 00:18:45.260
and it was this social justice
message that I think

00:18:45.260 --> 00:18:48.130
that really got him a hearing
among many of the folks.

00:18:48.130 --> 00:18:52.730
So coming with Islam, it was
a new order, a new way of life.

00:18:52.730 --> 00:18:54.330
And it was a beautiful
way of life

00:18:54.330 --> 00:18:56.360
because everybody was equal--

00:18:56.360 --> 00:18:58.760
black, white, men,
women, children.

00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:02.700
So it had that type
of universal appeal

00:19:02.700 --> 00:19:06.260
which I think was the reason
why Islam spread so rapidly.

00:19:07.900 --> 00:19:10.730
KINGSLEY:
Many were moved
by Muhammad's message

00:19:10.730 --> 00:19:14.560
as he began to speak out
in the community.

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:16.230
SELLS:
It had

00:19:16.230 --> 00:19:19.200
the suppleness
and symbolic depth

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:21.100
of the great Pre-Islamic poems

00:19:21.100 --> 00:19:24.330
that had been created
by this people

00:19:24.330 --> 00:19:27.960
and that had given
this people in Arabia

00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:32.230
such an extraordinary ear
for verbal expression

00:19:32.230 --> 00:19:38.100
where verbal expression was
<i> the</i> commanding cultural force.

00:19:38.100 --> 00:19:40.360
Some people called him a poet

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:45.400
and there's a Qur'anic surah,
basically saying

00:19:45.400 --> 00:19:47.830
Muhammad is not a poet.

00:19:47.830 --> 00:19:50.830
Poets speak through desire.

00:19:50.830 --> 00:19:54.700
This is not the voice of desire,
this is the voice of God.

00:19:58.500 --> 00:20:03.000
KINGSLEY:
Muhammad's following
began to grow.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:06.100
They called themselves Muslims

00:20:06.100 --> 00:20:10.830
for "those who
surrender to God."

00:20:10.830 --> 00:20:14.700
They set out to preserve the
message Muhammad had brought.

00:20:14.700 --> 00:20:17.860
This was the beginning
of the Qur'an.

00:20:19.660 --> 00:20:23.860
BLOOM:
The Qur'an was revealed orally,
but very soon people realized

00:20:23.860 --> 00:20:25.460
that it had to be written down

00:20:25.460 --> 00:20:27.900
in order to make sure
that it wasn't corrupted

00:20:27.900 --> 00:20:30.300
and that the original message
was maintained.

00:20:32.630 --> 00:20:34.460
And from a very early date--

00:20:34.460 --> 00:20:37.200
and it's very unclear
when that date was

00:20:37.200 --> 00:20:40.700
because no early manuscripts
of the Qur'an survive--

00:20:40.700 --> 00:20:43.960
people began copying it down.

00:20:47.300 --> 00:20:51.760
KINGSLEY:
The Qur'an is a revelation
of the spiritual teaching

00:20:51.760 --> 00:20:55.500
of both ethical
and social guidance.

00:20:55.500 --> 00:21:01.330
It was revealed
and remains in Arabic.

00:21:01.330 --> 00:21:05.330
SELLS:
What's so extraordinary about
the Qur'an is its naturalness

00:21:05.330 --> 00:21:09.460
so that it can say the most
powerful cosmic things

00:21:09.460 --> 00:21:11.500
with a sense of intimacy

00:21:11.500 --> 00:21:15.930
so that power and tenderness
come together constantly

00:21:15.930 --> 00:21:17.260
in the Qur'anic language.

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:20.630
With words alone

00:21:20.630 --> 00:21:24.660
the Qur'an delivers
its vision to the faithful.

00:21:24.660 --> 00:21:28.560
Its imagery conjures a picture
of the afterlife that resonates

00:21:28.560 --> 00:21:32.830
with all the power of
traditional Bedouin poetry.

00:21:34.960 --> 00:21:38.560
SELLS:
Imagine yourself in the desert

00:21:38.560 --> 00:21:43.630
surrounded by dust
and by the glare of the sun.

00:21:43.630 --> 00:21:45.360
You wear cloaks
to cover your body

00:21:45.360 --> 00:21:51.030
because the wind will just sear
your skin right off your face.

00:21:51.030 --> 00:21:56.260
And you walk into an oasis.

00:21:56.260 --> 00:21:59.300
The temperature drops
dramatically.

00:21:59.300 --> 00:22:01.330
There's a quiet there.

00:22:01.330 --> 00:22:04.730
The wind is no longer howling.

00:22:04.730 --> 00:22:09.300
Everywhere you look you see
green and color.

00:22:09.300 --> 00:22:12.560
The world of water and paradise

00:22:12.560 --> 00:22:16.530
are symbolically
tied to one another.

00:22:16.530 --> 00:22:18.530
And the Qur'an conjured that up

00:22:18.530 --> 00:22:22.160
with just a few
briefly chosen words.

00:22:30.730 --> 00:22:34.260
KINGSLEY:
Yet for all the imagery
of Paradise in the Qur'an

00:22:34.260 --> 00:22:37.660
there was no easy
description of God.

00:22:37.660 --> 00:22:41.530
The mystery would remain.

00:22:41.530 --> 00:22:45.960
SELLS:
It's very difficult to talk
about God without reifying God--

00:22:45.960 --> 00:22:48.330
"reifying"-- to make God
into a thing;

00:22:48.330 --> 00:22:50.200
or anthropomorphizing God--

00:22:50.200 --> 00:22:54.760
to make God into a projection
of our own human self.

00:22:54.760 --> 00:22:57.400
And that's why Muslims
don't like sculpture

00:22:57.400 --> 00:22:59.030
for example, traditionally

00:22:59.030 --> 00:23:01.930
because they believe
that there's that danger.

00:23:01.930 --> 00:23:06.000
And the Qur'an avoids that by
constantly shifting the pronouns

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:07.900
so we can't really reify God

00:23:07.900 --> 00:23:11.130
and get it... an image,
a physical image of God.

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:18.200
KINGSLEY:
Rather than a physical image
of God, or of Muhammad

00:23:18.200 --> 00:23:20.630
it is the beauty
of the Qur'an itself

00:23:20.630 --> 00:23:23.830
that is celebrated in Islam.

00:23:23.830 --> 00:23:30.800
BLOOM:
Islam developed in this context
where pictures were not favored.

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:33.030
The Qur'an, as it was revealed

00:23:33.030 --> 00:23:35.600
was God's
representation on earth

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:38.330
and Muslims felt,
from a very early time

00:23:38.330 --> 00:23:40.630
that the only
just representation

00:23:40.630 --> 00:23:42.300
of God... God's word

00:23:42.300 --> 00:23:44.060
was the Qur'an itself

00:23:44.060 --> 00:23:47.760
not any picture of...
of God, certainly not

00:23:47.760 --> 00:23:49.500
because you couldn't
represent God

00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:51.530
and certainly not
a picture of Muhammad

00:23:51.530 --> 00:23:52.800
because he wasn't divine.

00:24:01.700 --> 00:24:03.200
At certain times and places

00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:05.800
people did make images
of the prophet Muhammad.

00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:08.030
But these are not
religious images.

00:24:08.030 --> 00:24:10.900
These are not images
meant to be worshipped.

00:24:10.900 --> 00:24:14.000
They're not images
of a saint or of God.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:19.500
They're images of Muhammad
as a historical figure.

00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:21.100
He's sort of given honor

00:24:21.100 --> 00:24:23.660
by having a very bright
blue background

00:24:23.660 --> 00:24:25.630
or a white cloud near him.

00:24:25.630 --> 00:24:28.230
But he's not otherwise
distinguished

00:24:28.230 --> 00:24:30.400
from the other characters
in the story.

00:24:30.400 --> 00:24:32.830
At other times, people did
represent the prophet

00:24:32.830 --> 00:24:36.000
but he was always represented
with a white cloth over his face

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:37.630
to hide his face

00:24:37.630 --> 00:24:41.400
so that there were different
approaches to doing this.

00:24:43.230 --> 00:24:45.930
But in all of these,
these are not devotional images.

00:24:45.930 --> 00:24:48.900
You're not supposed to look
at them and pray towards them.

00:24:48.900 --> 00:24:52.060
You're to learn more about
the history of your religion

00:24:52.060 --> 00:24:55.260
with the emphasis on history
from them.

00:24:57.500 --> 00:25:03.760
KINGSLEY:
As Muhammad's community grew,
so did the opposition.

00:25:03.760 --> 00:25:06.830
SELLS:
People, of course,
were skeptical and said

00:25:06.830 --> 00:25:10.900
"Look, if you're a prophet,
where's your miracle?"

00:25:10.900 --> 00:25:13.560
And the prophets in the Qur'an--

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:17.460
Moses had miracles,
Jesus had miracles.

00:25:17.460 --> 00:25:19.200
"Where's your miracle?"

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:22.100
The Qur'anic answer
to that challenge

00:25:22.100 --> 00:25:27.300
is "This is the miracle,
this Qur'an."

00:25:30.830 --> 00:25:32.630
KINGSLEY:
But that wasn't miracle enough

00:25:32.630 --> 00:25:34.330
for the people
who defined themselves

00:25:34.330 --> 00:25:39.400
by the gods of their ancestors
and the totems of their tribe.

00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:42.660
Their doubts increased.

00:25:42.660 --> 00:25:46.960
The idea of life after death
appalled them.

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:51.900
SELLS:
So the Qur'an presents people
as really being skeptical:

00:25:51.900 --> 00:25:54.900
"You mean to tell me
that after I die

00:25:54.900 --> 00:25:58.300
"and my body has gone
back to the elements

00:25:58.300 --> 00:26:00.400
"and I've been putrefied

00:26:00.400 --> 00:26:03.400
"that I'm going to be put
back together again

00:26:03.400 --> 00:26:05.200
and brought back to life?"

00:26:05.200 --> 00:26:07.860
That... of any of
the messages in the Qur'an

00:26:07.860 --> 00:26:09.900
that struck the people of Arabia

00:26:09.900 --> 00:26:12.030
as being the most
hard to believe.

00:26:14.260 --> 00:26:19.360
KINGSLEY:
Muhammad also spoke of eternal
damnation for the unjust.

00:26:19.360 --> 00:26:22.100
RENARD:
He used the language
of apocalyptic imagery

00:26:22.100 --> 00:26:25.530
talking about the signs
of the ends of time;

00:26:25.530 --> 00:26:27.330
When the mountains crumble;

00:26:27.330 --> 00:26:31.530
When the skies are rolled up
like scrolls, then you will know

00:26:31.530 --> 00:26:34.700
what responsibility you bear
for your actions.

00:26:34.700 --> 00:26:36.860
There are references

00:26:36.860 --> 00:26:41.600
to those who are unjust
going to the fire.

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:48.930
KINGSLEY:
To the nonbelievers, the divine
reckoning Muhammad invoked

00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:53.860
was an outrage, his dismantling
of their heritage and customs

00:26:53.860 --> 00:26:56.200
deeply unsettling.

00:26:57.860 --> 00:26:58.960
DENNY:
It was a threat

00:26:58.960 --> 00:27:00.460
a threat in several ways:

00:27:00.460 --> 00:27:03.200
to their social order,
to their age-old traditions

00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:05.830
and an economic threat
because of the importance

00:27:05.830 --> 00:27:08.500
of the pilgrimage shrine
of the Ka'bah in Mecca.

00:27:12.400 --> 00:27:15.100
KINGSLEY:
As Muhammad's following
increased

00:27:15.100 --> 00:27:19.960
the social fabric of the
caravan city began to unravel.

00:27:19.960 --> 00:27:21.700
Business suffered

00:27:21.700 --> 00:27:25.600
as pilgrims and traders, worried
for their safety, left town.

00:27:27.530 --> 00:27:29.100
The tribal leaders decided

00:27:29.100 --> 00:27:36.560
Muhammad and his message
must be removed permanently.

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:38.300
RENARD:
They didn't want him
taking over.

00:27:38.300 --> 00:27:40.960
They didn't want him horning in
on their control of the city.

00:27:40.960 --> 00:27:42.930
They made things
very difficult for him

00:27:42.930 --> 00:27:44.900
perhaps even plotted
his assassination.

00:27:44.900 --> 00:27:47.130
They tried to keep him
away from the Ka'bah.

00:27:47.130 --> 00:27:49.900
They did everything they could
to try to run him out of town.

00:27:53.500 --> 00:27:56.000
KINGSLEY:
They demanded
that Muhammad's uncle remove

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:59.160
his clan's protection
from the prophet

00:27:59.160 --> 00:28:01.330
which would clear the way
for his murder

00:28:01.330 --> 00:28:04.030
without the threat
of retribution.

00:28:07.530 --> 00:28:10.660
But his uncle refused.

00:28:10.660 --> 00:28:13.760
The battle lines were drawn.

00:28:13.760 --> 00:28:19.660
Nothing short of tribal war
would settle the conflict now.

00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:24.260
SELLS:
Muhammad is clearly asked
to do extraordinary things:

00:28:24.260 --> 00:28:25.630
to tell the Bedouin

00:28:25.630 --> 00:28:30.700
to give up many of their notions
of multiple gods;

00:28:30.700 --> 00:28:32.860
to give up their attachment
to their ancestors

00:28:32.860 --> 00:28:36.330
and their tribal warfare
in the way they had--

00:28:36.330 --> 00:28:40.730
things that would...
could and did make him

00:28:40.730 --> 00:28:45.560
the object of scorn,
persecution and an attack.

00:28:51.530 --> 00:28:52.860
KINGSLEY:
Muhammad's followers

00:28:52.860 --> 00:28:57.730
were forced from
the marketplace and starved.

00:28:57.730 --> 00:29:02.560
Those without clan protection
were tortured and killed.

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:12.800
In 619 AD, Muhammad's wife,
Khadijah, died

00:29:12.800 --> 00:29:15.860
and his uncle as well.

00:29:15.860 --> 00:29:22.800
Gone were his first great love
and his only protector.

00:29:22.800 --> 00:29:24.260
Here at last

00:29:24.260 --> 00:29:31.530
was the opportunity his enemies
had been waiting for.

00:29:31.530 --> 00:29:36.430
But in the lush oasis town
of Yathrib, north of Mecca

00:29:36.430 --> 00:29:40.300
a refuge opens
to Muhammad and his people.

00:29:40.300 --> 00:29:43.960
Clan rivalries had become
deadly in the town

00:29:43.960 --> 00:29:47.400
and they desperately needed
a peacemaker.

00:29:47.400 --> 00:29:50.200
RENARD:
They had heard that Muhammad was
a very trustworthy man.

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:52.460
They'd heard that he had
great arbitration skills.

00:29:52.460 --> 00:29:54.000
And they thought

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:56.830
"We'll see if we can't get him
up here and help us out."

00:29:56.830 --> 00:29:59.300
So they invited him.

00:30:05.200 --> 00:30:07.730
KINGSLEY:
Muhammad agreed
to travel to Yathrib

00:30:07.730 --> 00:30:09.200
and settle their disputes

00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:11.760
in exchange for a safe refuge
for his people.

00:30:16.430 --> 00:30:19.300
For Muhammad's followers,
leaving the place

00:30:19.300 --> 00:30:22.330
of their ancestors,
their families and tribes

00:30:22.330 --> 00:30:25.400
was the ultimate test
of devotion.

00:30:31.800 --> 00:30:37.030
In doing so, they began
a new community, a new tribe.

00:30:39.300 --> 00:30:42.630
For the first time, they were
bound together not by blood

00:30:42.630 --> 00:30:45.030
but by faith.

00:30:50.300 --> 00:30:53.200
In the course of
a single caravan journey

00:30:53.200 --> 00:30:58.760
Islam marks its true beginnings.

00:30:58.760 --> 00:31:03.800
Their journey is known
as the<i> hijrah.</i>

00:31:03.800 --> 00:31:09.730
622 in the Christian calendar
marks the Muslim year one.

00:31:16.800 --> 00:31:19.460
Muhammad's goal among
the people of Yathrib

00:31:19.460 --> 00:31:22.060
was the same
as his larger mission:

00:31:22.060 --> 00:31:26.200
to bring unity and peace
with his message.

00:31:26.200 --> 00:31:29.830
SELLS:
He was asked to be
a Solomonic figure--

00:31:29.830 --> 00:31:36.400
to mediate tensions between
tribes that seemed intractable.

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:39.600
KINGSLEY:
As his work succeeded,
the town would become known

00:31:39.600 --> 00:31:44.560
as "the city of
the Prophet," Medina.

00:31:44.560 --> 00:31:46.230
RENARD:
Muhammad's great task in Medina

00:31:46.230 --> 00:31:48.860
was to try and bring together
these various groups

00:31:48.860 --> 00:31:54.000
and to try and forge
a community of believers

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:59.860
in a way that would bring people
together in a sort a harmony.

00:32:02.860 --> 00:32:05.400
KINGSLEY:
To the divided clans of Medina

00:32:05.400 --> 00:32:09.360
Muhammad offered
a vision of solidarity.

00:32:09.360 --> 00:32:12.000
But even as he spread
the word of Islam

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:16.760
he didn't challenge
the beliefs of other faiths.

00:32:16.760 --> 00:32:19.230
BLOOM:
Islam sees itself
in relationship

00:32:19.230 --> 00:32:21.630
to the earlier
revealed religions

00:32:21.630 --> 00:32:23.730
of Judaism and Christianity

00:32:23.730 --> 00:32:28.130
and treats them
as "people of the Book."

00:32:28.130 --> 00:32:33.300
It believes that God had
revealed himself, his word

00:32:33.300 --> 00:32:35.800
to mankind, many times--

00:32:35.800 --> 00:32:38.730
to Moses, to Jesus,
for example-- and...

00:32:38.730 --> 00:32:41.300
but each time,
people went astray.

00:32:44.360 --> 00:32:45.900
SELLS:
Throughout the Qur'an

00:32:45.900 --> 00:32:48.860
we have a sense of
the humanity of Muhammad

00:32:48.860 --> 00:32:50.730
his humbleness as a person

00:32:50.730 --> 00:32:56.100
and the extraordinary challenge
of the mission he was given

00:32:56.100 --> 00:32:59.230
by this divine revelation.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:07.260
KINGSLEY:
As the Muslim community grew
in Medina

00:33:07.260 --> 00:33:11.560
a life of simple devotion
and ritual developed.

00:33:11.560 --> 00:33:16.530
A freed Abyssinian slave,
named Bilal

00:33:16.530 --> 00:33:20.700
was the first to call believers
to prayer at Muhammad's house.

00:33:20.700 --> 00:33:26.130
(<i> muezzin making
 call to prayer</i> )

00:33:26.130 --> 00:33:28.030
KINGSLEY:
It was the first mosque.

00:33:38.460 --> 00:33:43.400
SELLS:
The call to prayer has within it
the first Islamic pillar

00:33:43.400 --> 00:33:46.530
which is the affirmation
of God's unity:

00:33:46.530 --> 00:33:48.830
<i>"La ilaha illa Allah"</i>

00:33:48.830 --> 00:33:51.730
that beautiful phrase,
which many Muslims chant

00:33:51.730 --> 00:33:54.060
over and over in their mind
or vocally

00:33:54.060 --> 00:33:57.960
to constantly remind themselves
of the unity of God

00:33:57.960 --> 00:34:02.700
and the unity of what
we should focus on in our life.

00:34:04.760 --> 00:34:07.160
<i>La ilaha illa Allah!</i>

00:34:07.160 --> 00:34:08.900
<i>Ashhadu inna</i>

00:34:08.900 --> 00:34:11.630
<i>La ilaha illa Allah!</i>

00:34:11.630 --> 00:34:12.760
<i>Ashhadu inna</i>

00:34:12.760 --> 00:34:14.460
<i>Muhammad rasul Allah!</i>

00:34:14.460 --> 00:34:18.600
DENNY:
Praying together
is a good thing.

00:34:18.600 --> 00:34:22.260
It cements the idea of belonging
to a movement or a religion

00:34:22.260 --> 00:34:26.400
to an organization,
to a community.

00:34:26.400 --> 00:34:28.360
MUEZZIN:
<i> Hayyu 'ala al-sala!</i>

00:34:28.360 --> 00:34:30.430
DENNY:
The result is

00:34:30.430 --> 00:34:33.100
something very,
very powerful even... to watch

00:34:33.100 --> 00:34:36.430
even for a nonbeliever or
someone from another religion.

00:34:36.430 --> 00:34:41.460
We carry out physical gestures
of prayer in worship

00:34:41.460 --> 00:34:45.900
that unify our body and our mind
and our soul

00:34:45.900 --> 00:34:48.460
all at the same moment of bowing

00:34:48.460 --> 00:34:51.230
and touching
our head to the ground

00:34:51.230 --> 00:34:53.660
toward that exact center.

00:34:53.660 --> 00:34:56.330
What could be
a more powerful symbol of unity?

00:34:59.130 --> 00:35:02.300
KINGSLEY:
It's said that
while he was in Medina

00:35:02.300 --> 00:35:07.230
Muhammad received a revelation
instructing those in prayer

00:35:07.230 --> 00:35:12.400
to face in the direction
of the Ka'bah, in Mecca.

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:14.760
Though filled with pagan idols

00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:17.430
it was still
the shrine of Abraham

00:35:17.430 --> 00:35:21.760
the first believer
in the one true God.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:28.300
But even as the Muslims
were praying toward Mecca

00:35:28.300 --> 00:35:31.360
their enemies there
were rallying in force.

00:35:31.360 --> 00:35:35.660
Their goal:
to wipe out the Muslims.

00:35:43.430 --> 00:35:46.000
Muhammad's people
began to gather arms.

00:35:52.630 --> 00:35:55.560
Though the Muslims prepared
as best they could

00:35:55.560 --> 00:35:58.660
they were outnumbered
and outmatched.

00:36:00.100 --> 00:36:03.560
They mustered a force
of only 313

00:36:03.560 --> 00:36:07.760
mostly old men and boys,
with few weapons...

00:36:09.760 --> 00:36:13.400
while the approaching Meccans
were heavily armed

00:36:13.400 --> 00:36:15.530
and a thousand strong.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:22.800
For years, Muhammad had tried
to bring Islam

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:24.960
to the people of Mecca
peacefully.

00:36:24.960 --> 00:36:28.030
Now it was time to fight.

00:36:44.900 --> 00:36:48.400
The Muslims faced
their own tribes--

00:36:48.400 --> 00:36:53.730
brother fighting brother,
son against father.

00:36:56.800 --> 00:37:00.930
Yet they came armed
with a powerful weapon:

00:37:00.930 --> 00:37:04.030
a passionate belief
in their faith.

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:07.100
Muhammad's troops fought

00:37:07.100 --> 00:37:11.630
with every confidence that
God's will was guiding them.

00:37:16.930 --> 00:37:20.060
They fought three
very, very bloody battles.

00:37:20.060 --> 00:37:23.460
At one point, the entire
young Muslim community

00:37:23.460 --> 00:37:25.430
was right on the edge
of annihilation.

00:37:33.230 --> 00:37:35.000
KINGSLEY:
For three years

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:38.530
the Muslim army held out
against staggering odds.

00:37:48.030 --> 00:37:50.130
As word of the fighting spread

00:37:50.130 --> 00:37:57.160
other Bedouin tribes saw God's
hand in Muhammad's victories.

00:37:57.160 --> 00:37:58.700
One by one

00:37:58.700 --> 00:38:02.430
the peoples of the desert
began to join in his struggle.

00:38:02.430 --> 00:38:07.100
The Muslim army grew,
and the tide began to turn.

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:19.960
The Muslim forces advanced
to the outskirts of Mecca.

00:38:22.700 --> 00:38:25.600
It was a furious siege that
lasted for nearly a month...

00:38:29.130 --> 00:38:33.560
Until finally,
the city fell to Muhammad.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:41.360
In 630 AD

00:38:41.360 --> 00:38:44.760
the terrified people of Mecca
braced for the onslaught.

00:38:47.330 --> 00:38:54.200
Muhammad's army was returning
home, now 10,000 strong.

00:39:02.800 --> 00:39:08.230
The vanquished knew the terrible
fate that awaited them.

00:39:08.230 --> 00:39:11.730
SELLS:
According to the modes
of tribal warfare

00:39:11.730 --> 00:39:15.800
the Meccans could expect
a big revenge.

00:39:15.800 --> 00:39:18.300
The men are usually killed.

00:39:18.300 --> 00:39:24.460
Women and children
are sold into slavery.

00:39:24.460 --> 00:39:28.600
There's little pity for
the loser in a tribal war.

00:39:31.860 --> 00:39:35.560
Of course, that's standard
around the world.

00:39:39.100 --> 00:39:44.760
KINGSLEY:
But Muhammad had a surprise
in store for the fallen city.

00:39:44.760 --> 00:39:46.830
When Muhammad came into Mecca

00:39:46.830 --> 00:39:50.160
and not only did not carry out
a bloody revenge

00:39:50.160 --> 00:39:51.530
but actually embraced

00:39:51.530 --> 00:39:54.730
the very Meccans who had
fought him for three years

00:39:54.730 --> 00:39:56.760
and attempted to annihilate him

00:39:56.760 --> 00:40:05.030
it was very shocking
to the people in his milieu.

00:40:05.030 --> 00:40:09.430
So within the very founding
of the religion

00:40:09.430 --> 00:40:14.400
one finds episodes
of great generosity

00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:18.830
often extraordinary acts
of kindness and mercy.

00:40:21.960 --> 00:40:25.100
KINGSLEY:
But not all of Mecca
escaped Muhammad's wrath.

00:40:26.930 --> 00:40:28.460
(<i> crowd ululating</i> )

00:40:28.460 --> 00:40:34.730
Flush with victory, his troops
marched straight to the Ka'bah.

00:40:34.730 --> 00:40:37.730
Seven times
they circled the shrine

00:40:37.730 --> 00:40:39.730
as those who had come
to seek its protection

00:40:39.730 --> 00:40:43.560
appealed to their idols.

00:40:43.560 --> 00:40:48.460
But it was not the pagan people
Muhammad had come to destroy.

00:40:48.460 --> 00:40:52.530
It was their gods.

00:40:52.530 --> 00:40:54.700
He raised his staff

00:40:54.700 --> 00:41:00.060
and the tribal gods of his
ancestors smashed into dust.

00:41:00.060 --> 00:41:05.100
SELLS:
When Muhammad entered Mecca
and entered the shrine

00:41:05.100 --> 00:41:08.430
and destroyed the idols
of the shrine

00:41:08.430 --> 00:41:14.960
this is of great cultural and
symbolic importance in Islam.

00:41:14.960 --> 00:41:17.660
By breaking the idols

00:41:17.660 --> 00:41:22.730
he was breaking apart
the tribal system

00:41:22.730 --> 00:41:29.860
in which each tribe really had
its own independent deity.

00:41:29.860 --> 00:41:31.960
This was shocking
to the Bedouin.

00:41:31.960 --> 00:41:33.400
This was saying

00:41:33.400 --> 00:41:36.400
"The gods of our fathers
are being destroyed.

00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:37.800
"In some sense you're saying

00:41:37.800 --> 00:41:41.600
"that our fathers themselves
were deluded.

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:44.000
"How can you say this
in a tradition

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:48.200
in which relationships to one's
father and tribe are primary?"

00:41:48.200 --> 00:41:52.600
So this act of iconoclasm,
then, is seen

00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:55.700
as an act of prophetic violence

00:41:55.700 --> 00:42:01.000
that has just as much importance
in Islamic tradition

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:04.500
as Moses' breaking
of the tablets

00:42:04.500 --> 00:42:07.730
when he saw the idolatry
of Mount Sinai

00:42:07.730 --> 00:42:13.160
or Jesus' casting the
money-sellers out of the temple.

00:42:17.800 --> 00:42:21.830
KINGSLEY:
The destruction of the idols
was a new beginning

00:42:21.830 --> 00:42:24.430
a breaking from the past

00:42:24.430 --> 00:42:28.760
and the creation
of a powerful new force.

00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:32.230
Mecca was just the beginning.

00:42:32.230 --> 00:42:33.830
One after another

00:42:33.830 --> 00:42:38.360
the tribes of a nation were
summoned to the fold

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:41.830
and united
under the banner of Islam.

00:42:41.830 --> 00:42:45.960
A worldwide community
of faith was begun

00:42:45.960 --> 00:42:49.560
borne in an extraordinary
alignment

00:42:49.560 --> 00:42:52.060
of history, personality
and conviction.

00:42:53.760 --> 00:42:56.730
ATIL:
What Muhammad did was to bring

00:42:56.730 --> 00:43:00.230
a sense of solidarity,
a sense of mission

00:43:00.230 --> 00:43:03.060
and he united all these
separate segments

00:43:03.060 --> 00:43:04.630
within the peninsula

00:43:04.630 --> 00:43:08.700
from then on, moved eastward,
westward, northward, southward.

00:43:13.400 --> 00:43:16.460
KINGSLEY:
The Muslims turned to the north

00:43:16.460 --> 00:43:19.560
swept into present-day Lebanon
and Syria.

00:43:25.500 --> 00:43:30.060
They continued west into Egypt
and quickly across North Africa

00:43:30.060 --> 00:43:33.460
fortifying the coastline
of the Mediterranean.

00:43:35.200 --> 00:43:38.030
Only the seas stopped them.

00:43:40.400 --> 00:43:41.700
Its growth was so explosive

00:43:41.700 --> 00:43:47.430
from 622, the year one
of the Islamic calendar.

00:43:47.430 --> 00:43:51.330
Um, within 50 years

00:43:51.330 --> 00:43:55.700
people whose father had been
camel herders

00:43:55.700 --> 00:44:00.130
were now governing one of the
major empires in world history.

00:44:00.130 --> 00:44:05.460
Within 200 years, it extended
from Spain to China.

00:44:08.400 --> 00:44:12.700
KINGSLEY:
The Muslims absorbed
the Sasanian Empire of Iran

00:44:12.700 --> 00:44:15.900
and two-thirds of the Christian
Byzantine Empire.

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:22.630
By now, the empire was larger
than Rome.

00:44:22.630 --> 00:44:25.430
It stretched from Morocco
in the west

00:44:25.430 --> 00:44:27.860
to the Indus River in the East

00:44:27.860 --> 00:44:30.560
where the border
of India is today.

00:44:36.330 --> 00:44:39.830
How had it happened
that so small an army

00:44:39.830 --> 00:44:44.930
could conquer an area so large
so fast, so easily?

00:44:48.360 --> 00:44:51.230
RENARD:
Islam's success in expanding

00:44:51.230 --> 00:44:55.330
into the central Middle East
and across North Africa

00:44:55.330 --> 00:44:57.030
was due in large part

00:44:57.030 --> 00:44:59.930
because people were fed up
with previous regimes.

00:44:59.930 --> 00:45:04.760
Well, the idea that Muslims
were going across the world

00:45:04.760 --> 00:45:10.000
saying, "Convert or die," is
really not accurate, not at all.

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:12.300
But it didn't have a heavy hand;

00:45:12.300 --> 00:45:14.760
they didn't rule
with a heavy hand.

00:45:14.760 --> 00:45:17.130
They allowed
the conquered peoples

00:45:17.130 --> 00:45:20.260
to maintain
their administrative structures.

00:45:20.260 --> 00:45:22.800
They allowed the Christians
and the Jews

00:45:22.800 --> 00:45:26.560
to maintain their religious law
and to be governed by them.

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:29.900
And so in many cases,
conquered peoples did not feel

00:45:29.900 --> 00:45:32.700
the presence of the new regime
very heavily.

00:45:32.700 --> 00:45:34.900
Certainly for individuals

00:45:34.900 --> 00:45:38.760
who felt themselves
exploited or downtrodden

00:45:38.760 --> 00:45:42.000
by an oppressive and even
sometimes parasitic priesthood

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:43.430
the idea of Islam being

00:45:43.430 --> 00:45:45.800
a religion essentially free
from clergy

00:45:45.800 --> 00:45:47.830
must have seemed
very attractive.

00:45:50.700 --> 00:45:54.130
ATIL:
It's the times
that creates the movement

00:45:54.130 --> 00:45:55.900
and sometimes the men.

00:45:55.900 --> 00:45:57.900
The Roman Empire had collapsed;

00:45:57.900 --> 00:46:00.700
the Byzantine Empire
wasn't strong enough.

00:46:00.700 --> 00:46:03.500
There was a need
for a new vision

00:46:03.500 --> 00:46:06.730
a new way of looking to life.

00:46:06.730 --> 00:46:09.300
And I think what
happened at that time:

00:46:09.300 --> 00:46:13.700
Muhammad's mission filled the
void that the societies wanted.

00:46:13.700 --> 00:46:17.930
They really wanted some sort
of solidarity in their lives.

00:46:20.300 --> 00:46:22.400
KINGSLEY:
The lessons of the Koran

00:46:22.400 --> 00:46:25.500
so successful for the Muslims
in Medina and Mecca

00:46:25.500 --> 00:46:28.560
were playing out
on a global scale.

00:46:32.300 --> 00:46:35.400
As the conquest swept
through Syria

00:46:35.400 --> 00:46:38.400
the Muslims held
their Friday prayers

00:46:38.400 --> 00:46:42.530
in the Church of St. John
the Baptist in Damascus

00:46:42.530 --> 00:46:44.900
allowing its Christian
congregation

00:46:44.900 --> 00:46:47.430
to continue their services
on Sunday.

00:46:51.330 --> 00:46:53.130
Side by side

00:46:53.130 --> 00:46:58.700
the two faiths shared
the same building in peace.

00:47:04.360 --> 00:47:06.130
As the Muslim community grew

00:47:06.130 --> 00:47:09.760
they bought the old church
from the Christian congregation

00:47:09.760 --> 00:47:12.660
and built a huge mosque
on the site.

00:47:21.030 --> 00:47:22.760
With Byzantine artisans

00:47:22.760 --> 00:47:27.300
they decorated it with golden
mosaics of an Islamic paradise.

00:47:32.760 --> 00:47:36.460
The great mosque of Damascus
would become a model

00:47:36.460 --> 00:47:40.030
for new mosques to come,
all across the empire.

00:47:46.330 --> 00:47:50.030
The Arabs transformed
their conquered lands

00:47:50.030 --> 00:47:53.730
maintaining, improving or
expanding the infrastructure.

00:47:57.330 --> 00:47:59.930
In Tunisia, building
on Roman ruins

00:47:59.930 --> 00:48:04.100
they devised an ingenious system
of water purification

00:48:04.100 --> 00:48:08.130
using gravity to separate
freshwater from sediments.

00:48:09.830 --> 00:48:13.800
BLOOM:
Part of this system were
these two enormous basins

00:48:13.800 --> 00:48:16.800
that they built
outside the city walls

00:48:18.430 --> 00:48:24.330
The clean freshwater would flow
over into the larger basin

00:48:24.330 --> 00:48:27.700
where it would then be
distributed by pipes

00:48:27.700 --> 00:48:28.900
to the city.

00:48:28.900 --> 00:48:31.160
This is, you know,
hundreds of years

00:48:31.160 --> 00:48:33.500
before anyone in Europe
ever thought

00:48:33.500 --> 00:48:35.130
of having running water.

00:48:46.160 --> 00:48:49.030
All over, you find schemes
for bringing water

00:48:49.030 --> 00:48:51.930
from the mountains
where there was more water

00:48:51.930 --> 00:48:54.900
to the plains
where there might be less water.

00:48:57.700 --> 00:49:01.230
KINGSLEY:
They resurrected
elaborate irrigation systems

00:49:01.230 --> 00:49:04.600
filling the old stone aqueducts
with precious water.

00:49:09.460 --> 00:49:12.900
Agriculture flourished, as
life-giving staples like wheat

00:49:12.900 --> 00:49:15.560
were introduced
to the Mediterranean region.

00:49:22.200 --> 00:49:26.100
But Muslims saved
their most monumental feat

00:49:26.100 --> 00:49:28.760
for the holy city of Jerusalem.

00:49:30.400 --> 00:49:34.860
BLOOM:
Islam's first great work of art
is the Dome of the Rock.

00:49:34.860 --> 00:49:39.300
It was built in a city that was
holy to Christians and Jews

00:49:39.300 --> 00:49:40.530
and it's spectacular.

00:49:44.600 --> 00:49:47.030
KINGSLEY:
Like Mecca and the Ka'bah

00:49:47.030 --> 00:49:50.900
the significance of this holy
site goes back to Abraham

00:49:50.900 --> 00:49:53.230
for the rock within
is said to be

00:49:53.230 --> 00:49:56.260
the place he nearly
sacrificed his son.

00:49:59.160 --> 00:50:03.100
It was built to rival the nearby
Church of the Holy Sepulcher

00:50:03.100 --> 00:50:07.760
where Jesus was said
to have been buried.

00:50:07.760 --> 00:50:12.500
BLOOM:
What's extraordinary
about the Dome of the Rock

00:50:12.500 --> 00:50:14.430
is how perfect it is.

00:50:14.430 --> 00:50:16.130
People revered this site

00:50:16.130 --> 00:50:19.830
as someplace that was holy
to Abraham and to Isaac.

00:50:23.760 --> 00:50:27.760
Imagine, if you will,
these new guys coming in

00:50:27.760 --> 00:50:29.830
and taking over this piece
of prime real estate.

00:50:31.960 --> 00:50:36.400
And building a new building
for a new religion

00:50:36.400 --> 00:50:38.330
that sits on top of a mountain

00:50:38.330 --> 00:50:43.730
and sparkles and glitters in the
sunlight for everyone to see.

00:50:44.930 --> 00:50:48.030
This is not something
fly-by-night.

00:50:48.030 --> 00:50:52.660
This is something big
and important.

00:50:52.660 --> 00:50:56.530
Islam has come to stay.

00:50:56.530 --> 00:50:58.830
KINGSLEY:
In just a hundred years

00:50:58.830 --> 00:51:01.060
Muhammad's vision
had transformed

00:51:01.060 --> 00:51:04.330
the spiritual and political map
of the world.

00:51:04.330 --> 00:51:06.230
And his followers
had established

00:51:06.230 --> 00:51:09.100
an empire larger than Rome.

00:51:11.030 --> 00:51:15.030
But Muhammad never lived
to see it.

00:51:17.600 --> 00:51:23.630
In the 11th year of the Islamic
calendar-- 632 AD--

00:51:23.630 --> 00:51:29.330
only two years after the taking
of Mecca, Muhammad died.

00:51:29.330 --> 00:51:34.330
(<i> men shouting,
 women ululating</i> )

00:51:34.330 --> 00:51:37.400
KINGSLEY:
Medina fell into despair

00:51:37.400 --> 00:51:39.800
(<i> women ululating,
 men shouting</i> )

00:51:39.800 --> 00:51:45.160
KINGSLEY:
For days, the city was consumed
with sorrow and ceremony.

00:51:45.160 --> 00:51:48.830
BLOOM:
He's known to have said that he
wanted to be buried very simply

00:51:48.830 --> 00:51:50.600
with no marker over his grave.

00:51:50.600 --> 00:51:53.100
He didn't want people
to worship his grave.

00:51:53.100 --> 00:51:56.530
That would interfere
with their worship of God.

00:51:56.530 --> 00:52:01.330
KINGSLEY:
God had spoken to them
only through Muhammad.

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:04.300
Now that the prophet
had left them

00:52:04.300 --> 00:52:06.630
perhaps God would as well.

00:52:06.630 --> 00:52:11.230
RENARD:
Muhammad's death set up a crisis
in the young Islamic community.

00:52:11.230 --> 00:52:13.760
The question of succession
was the first thing

00:52:13.760 --> 00:52:16.360
that really occupied
people's concerns.

00:52:16.360 --> 00:52:18.530
At this point, there was
a divergence of opinion

00:52:18.530 --> 00:52:22.000
as to how the community should
go about choosing a new leader.

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:26.100
According to the Shiites,
the faction-- the Shi'a-- of Ali

00:52:26.100 --> 00:52:28.560
Muhammad had indeed
designated Ali

00:52:28.560 --> 00:52:31.700
his son-in-law and cousin,
as his successor.

00:52:31.700 --> 00:52:35.000
The opinion that came to be
the majority opinion

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:36.400
or the Sunni opinion

00:52:36.400 --> 00:52:39.560
held that Muhammad had not
appointed a successor

00:52:39.560 --> 00:52:41.130
during his life

00:52:41.130 --> 00:52:45.030
but had said, "After I'm gone,
choose one from among your peers

00:52:45.030 --> 00:52:46.660
from among the elders."

00:52:47.860 --> 00:52:50.160
And from the house
there came out

00:52:50.160 --> 00:52:54.360
the man who would be
his successor, Abu Bakr.

00:52:54.360 --> 00:52:57.100
And he addressed the people
and said

00:52:57.100 --> 00:53:00.230
"If you worship Muhammad,
know that he is dead.

00:53:00.230 --> 00:53:03.400
If you worship God,
know that he lives forever."

00:53:05.830 --> 00:53:12.030
KINGSLEY:
Here was the secret to Islam's
strength and profound influence:

00:53:12.030 --> 00:53:17.030
the unifying power of one God--
merciful and compassionate--

00:53:17.030 --> 00:53:21.160
the power of one people
bound by a common faith.

00:53:23.330 --> 00:53:26.360
Muhammad did not lead
the conquest

00:53:26.360 --> 00:53:29.060
or create the empire to come;

00:53:29.060 --> 00:53:32.900
the transforming power
of his message did.

00:53:36.130 --> 00:53:40.460
Out of that message would spring
a font of knowledge

00:53:40.460 --> 00:53:42.930
that would transform humanity

00:53:42.930 --> 00:53:48.030
as Islam continued to spread
its reach far and wide.

00:53:49.800 --> 00:53:53.160
Awaiting the Muslims
would be a new age.

00:53:53.160 --> 00:53:56.560
They would be destined
for enlightenment

00:53:56.560 --> 00:54:00.500
for new horizons,
and a clash of great powers

00:54:00.500 --> 00:54:04.330
the like of which
the world had never seen.

00:54:13.230 --> 00:54:17.000
a powerful new faith was about
oto change the world--

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:19.160
the faith of Islam.

00:54:20.800 --> 00:54:24.860
Its followers launched a
conquest not only by the sword

00:54:24.860 --> 00:54:26.830
but with the power of ideas.

00:54:28.430 --> 00:54:31.360
200 years after the death
of Muhammad

00:54:31.360 --> 00:54:35.630
his message and the new Arab
Empire were transforming

00:54:35.630 --> 00:54:37.030
three continents.

00:54:39.400 --> 00:54:42.300
MAN:
Now comes a new empire

00:54:42.300 --> 00:54:45.760
a politically new configuration

00:54:45.760 --> 00:54:50.600
and driven by a religious,
newly defined civilization...

00:54:50.600 --> 00:54:55.330
this new civilization expanding
beyond its own dreams

00:54:55.330 --> 00:54:58.260
within a period
of very short time...

00:55:00.230 --> 00:55:04.700
literally the largest empire
civilization had ever known.

